[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.10: Clinical Trial Recruitment Conversationalist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per engaged candidate (depends on conversation depth, eligibility-criterion complexity, channel mix, model choice, IRB-approved-content depth, and research-coordinator handoff overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A clinical trial coordinator named Marisol works at an academic medical center in the Southwest. She has been a research coordinator for nine years. Right now she is running point on the recruitment for a Phase III trial of a new GLP-1 agonist for adults with type 2 diabetes who have inadequate glycemic control on metformin alone. The protocol calls for 240 participants at her site over an eighteen-month enrollment window. The enrollment-rate target is approximately 13 to 14 participants per month. Marisol is currently averaging four. She is, by her count, twelve months from the projected end-of-enrollment date and tracking to miss the target by more than 100 participants.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is not because Marisol is bad at her job. Marisol is excellent at her job. The bottleneck is not Marisol; the bottleneck is the recruitment funnel. The funnel works like this. Every two weeks, the institution's research-informatics team runs a query against the EHR's data warehouse for adults with a type 2 diabetes problem-list entry, an active metformin prescription, an HbA1c in the past 90 days between 7.5 and 10.5 percent, no contraindicating diagnoses (active malignancy, end-stage renal disease, pancreatitis history, certain endocrine conditions, certain GI conditions, pregnancy, others), and no exclusionary medications. The query returns a list. For Marisol's site, the list is typically 200 to 350 patients per cycle. Marisol's team prints out the list, sorts it, and starts working it down. The work-down is the problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For each patient on the list, the work consists of: pulling the chart to verify the inclusion and exclusion criteria the query could not evaluate (medication adherence in practice, comorbid conditions documented narratively, recent labs trending in concerning directions, contraindicating life events the chart references); sending a recruitment letter that the IRB has approved to the patient's address on file (about a third are returned undelivered); calling the patient at the phone number on file (about half don't answer; of those who do, about a quarter say they're not interested before any explanation, about a quarter say they're interested but never call back, and about half are interested enough to schedule a screening visit); conducting the screening visit (about 30 to 40 percent of those who show up are eligible after the full screen; the rest fail on a criterion that wasn't visible in the chart). The funnel from EHR-query-list to enrolled participant is about 3 to 5 percent at Marisol's site, which is in line with the published averages for clinical-trial recruitment. <!-- TODO: verify; clinical-trial recruitment funnel conversion rates vary substantially by therapeutic area, indication, and study design, with published averages typically in the low single digits for many therapeutic areas; specific figures vary by source -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The work that Marisol's team does in those phone calls is the work this recipe is about. The phone calls have a structure. The opening is brief: identify the institution, identify the study, ask if the person has a moment to hear about a research opportunity. If yes, the coordinator explains the study at a layperson level: the research question, the experimental treatment, the placebo arm, the visit schedule, the time commitment, the compensation, the risks at a high level, and the right of the participant to leave the study at any time. The coordinator then asks a structured set of pre-screen questions designed to rule out the major exclusion criteria the chart could not have surfaced (current pregnancy or planning pregnancy, recent or planned surgical procedures, recent travel restrictions affecting visit attendance, current participation in another interventional trial, certain life events). If the patient passes pre-screen and remains interested, the coordinator schedules a screening visit. The whole thing, when it goes well, takes 12 to 20 minutes per call. The whole thing, when the patient is not interested or not eligible, takes 3 to 8 minutes per call. Marisol's team makes about 60 to 80 calls per week per coordinator, with two coordinators at her site for this study. Most of the conversation script is identical from call to call, modulo language and reading-level adaptation. Most of the structured pre-screen questions are identical from call to call. Most of the inclusion and exclusion criteria are unambiguous yes-or-no facts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is, by structure, exactly the kind of work that a carefully-designed conversational AI can support. The patient gets a structured conversation about the study at any time of day, in their preferred language, at their preferred reading level, with consistent IRB-approved messaging, with the same patience for the third repetition of a clarifying question that the first one got. The patient can answer pre-screen questions when it is convenient for them, not when Marisol's team is at their desk. The patient can ask follow-up questions about the visit schedule, the compensation, or the experimental nature of the treatment, and get answers grounded in the IRB-approved study materials rather than ad-libbed by a coordinator who has explained this study three hundred times and may have gotten lazy on a particular phrasing. The candidates who would not have answered the phone, who would not have read the letter, who would not have called back, but who do reply to a text or open an app notification, become reachable. The pre-screen funnel runs faster, with the structured-data outputs piped directly into the trial's data system. Marisol's team gets a queue of pre-screened, interested, and eligibility-likely candidates with their structured pre-screen results attached, ready for the screening-visit scheduling work that actually requires Marisol's clinical judgment and relationship-building skill.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m That is the upside, and it is meaningful. The downside, and it is also meaningful, is that the regulatory, ethical, and clinical surfaces here are some of the most carefully-policed in healthcare. Clinical-trial recruitment communication is regulated. The communication scripts must be IRB-approved before deployment, and any meaningful change to the scripts requires IRB re-approval. <!-- TODO: verify; IRB approval of recruitment materials including scripts is required under the Common Rule (45 CFR 46) and FDA regulations (21 CFR Part 50 and 21 CFR Part 56); specific approval workflows vary by IRB --> The communication cannot promise benefit. The communication cannot disparage standard care. The communication cannot exaggerate the experimental treatment's prospects. The communication must clearly state the experimental nature of the treatment and the existence of the placebo arm where one is in the design. The communication must not coerce, must not pressure, must not exploit the power imbalance between the institution and the patient. The communication must respect the patient's right to decline without consequence to their ongoing care. The communication must protect PHI, with the additional consideration that even being contacted about a specific trial reveals that the institution has identified the patient as plausibly eligible, which itself is information about the patient's health status. <!-- TODO: verify; HIPAA's preparatory-research provisions and IRB-approved waiver-of-authorization frameworks govern the use of PHI for recruitment outreach with specific procedural requirements --> The communication must accommodate special-population considerations: pregnant patients, prisoners, children, cognitively-impaired adults, and other populations with vulnerability protections under the Common Rule have specific consent and recruitment-communication considerations. <!-- TODO: verify; the Common Rule (45 CFR 46) Subparts B, C, and D address additional protections for pregnant women, prisoners, and children respectively; FDA regulations have analogous provisions --> The communication must handle the specific state-by-state and country-by-country variation in research-recruitment regulation if the trial is multi-site or international. The bot is not a substitute for informed consent; the bot's role ends well before the informed-consent process begins. The handoff from bot to research coordinator is structurally important and is not a fallback; it is the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few additional things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that engages potential clinical-trial candidates in conversation about a specific trial, delivers IRB-approved study information at the right reading level and in the right language, conducts a structured pre-screen against the trial's inclusion and exclusion criteria, surfaces the research coordinator for the screening-visit scheduling and informed-consent process, and emits the structured pre-screen output to the institution's clinical-trial management system. It is the bot that handles the high-volume top-of-funnel work and frees the research coordinator to handle the work that actually requires their clinical judgment and relationship-building skill.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not the informed-consent process. Informed consent is an in-person (or, in some designs, video-based) conversation between the candidate and a study clinician, conducted with an IRB-approved consent document, with documented patient understanding and signed consent. The bot does not deliver informed consent. The bot prepares the candidate to engage productively with the consent process; the consent process itself is human-led.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not the screening visit. The screening visit involves clinical evaluation, lab work, imaging where applicable, and clinical-team judgment about study eligibility. The bot does the pre-screen against criteria that can be assessed conversationally; the bot does not do the screening visit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a replacement for the research coordinator. The research coordinator is the architecture; the bot is a force multiplier for the coordinator. A bot deployed without research-coordinator capacity to handle the downstream queue is a bot that generates leads with no one to convert them. The downstream coordinator capacity is sized to the bot's expected output, with appropriate buffer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for an IRB-approved recruitment plan. The bot's conversational scripts, the bot's pre-screen instrument, the bot's response to candidate questions, the bot's referral to the coordinator, and the bot's data-handling posture are all part of the IRB-reviewed recruitment plan for the specific trial. A bot deployed without trial-specific IRB approval is a bot in regulatory-violation territory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-trial pattern. Different trials have different inclusion and exclusion criteria, different study designs, different patient populations, different visit-schedule complexity, different compensation structures, and different IRB-approved messaging. The bot is multi-tenant across trials, with per-trial configuration, per-trial IRB-approved scripts, per-trial pre-screen instruments, and per-trial coordinator routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The first-trial deployment is multi-quarter clinical, regulatory, and engineering work. Subsequent trials, with the platform in place, deploy faster (typical incremental deployment cost is in weeks-to-months for trials similar to ones already running on the platform).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in the cleverness of its conversation. The value is in three places: the consistent IRB-approved messaging delivered at scale across the funnel (every candidate gets the same study description, with the same reading level adaptation, in their preferred language); the structured pre-screen output (the coordinator gets a candidate with their pre-screen answers pre-filled in the CTMS, not a candidate they have to ask the same questions again); and the funnel-throughput improvement (the coordinator's time is concentrated on the candidates who pass pre-screen and remain interested, not on the candidates who would have failed pre-screen anyway). A bot evaluated on engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on funnel-throughput improvement, on screening-visit-show-rate, on screening-visit-eligibility rate, on enrollment rate, on candidate diversity, and on coordinator-time-per-enrollment is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[K
