[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: IRB-Governed Conversational Recruitment, Pre-Screening, and Structured Coordinator Handoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Clinical-Trial Recruitment Has Resisted Digital Tools, and Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical-trial recruitment, as a workflow, has been an underperforming part of the research enterprise for decades. Most trials miss enrollment targets. Most enrollment misses extend study timelines, increase study costs, and (in the worst cases) terminate studies before they can answer the research question. The published averages on the central recruitment-funnel conversion rates are sobering: a meaningful fraction of trials do not enroll a single participant at a meaningful fraction of their initiated sites, and recruitment-related costs constitute a large fraction of total trial cost. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on clinical-trial recruitment underperformance is substantial, with figures varying by therapeutic area, trial design, and decade; sources include Tufts CSDD reports and FDA guidance on recruitment improvement -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The reason is structural, not technological. Recruitment is, fundamentally, a high-volume, high-touch communication problem with regulated content, vulnerable counterparties, and asymmetric information. The institution knows the candidate is plausibly eligible because it has the candidate's chart. The candidate does not know the trial exists. The institution wants the candidate to consider the trial; the candidate has not been thinking about a trial and may have very little context for why they should. The communication must be persuasive enough to engage a patient who was not seeking the conversation, while being scrupulously non-coercive, non-deceptive, and non-exploitative. The communication must be informative enough that the candidate can decide whether to engage further, while not crossing into informed-consent territory that requires a specific clinical context. The communication must collect enough structured data to advance the funnel, while not collecting more PHI than the IRB-approved recruitment plan permits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Digital tools have made dents in pieces of this workflow over the years. EHR-data-warehouse queries replaced manual chart review for the cohort-identification step. Email and text messaging replaced postal mail for the outreach step in many designs. Online pre-screening forms (REDCap pre-screens, study-website intake forms) replaced phone-based pre-screen for some trials. Per-trial recruitment websites replaced paper recruitment materials in many designs. Recruitment vendors built per-trial outreach campaigns through digital advertising channels. These tools improved specific funnel steps but did not change the fundamental shape of the workflow, which remained: identify a cohort, push outreach into the cohort, collect interest signals, route interested candidates through pre-screen, hand the survivors to a coordinator for a screening visit. The throughput improvements from each tool tended to be incremental, and the funnel conversion rates remained, in aggregate, low.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can carry on a structured, informative, IRB-script-grounded conversation with a candidate, in the candidate's preferred language and reading level, at the time of day the candidate is willing to engage. A conversational tool, deployed with careful IRB governance, can deliver the IRB-approved study description in conversational form rather than as a static block of text the candidate must read; can adapt the explanation to the candidate's specific questions ("what does randomization mean?" "what happens if I don't get the experimental treatment?" "is the placebo a sugar pill?") with answers grounded in the IRB-approved recruitment-content corpus; can conduct a structured pre-screen against the trial's inclusion and exclusion criteria with the IRB-approved instrument language; can surface the research coordinator with the structured pre-screen output and the conversation context attached; and can do this at scale across multiple concurrent trials with per-trial governance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "static recruitment materials and human-driven outreach" to "conversational interface that delivers IRB-approved content, conducts structured pre-screen, and routes warmly to the research coordinator." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the consistency of IRB-approved messaging across candidates (every candidate gets the same study description, with the same reading-level and language adaptation, with the same regulatory disclaimers), the structured-pre-screen output (the coordinator's pre-screen worksheet arrives pre-filled), and the funnel throughput improvement (the coordinator's time is concentrated where it has the most leverage).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what the recruitment bot is and is not, because the category overlaps with adjacent products that have different scope and risk profiles. The careful end of the spectrum is structured IRB-approved recruitment-content delivery with structured pre-screen and warm handoff to a research coordinator (this recipe). The middle of the spectrum is general-purpose patient-engagement chatbots that happen to mention available trials. The risky end of the spectrum is recruitment chatbots deployed without trial-specific IRB approval, without a structured pre-screen against IRB-approved criteria, without coordinator handoff capacity, or with messaging that crosses into the coercive, the misleading, or the inappropriately-promotional. The architectural decisions in this recipe are decisions about which end of the spectrum the deployment lives on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Clinical-Trial Recruitment Conversationalist Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A clinical-trial recruitment conversationalist, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the active trial's IRB-approved study description, the active trial's IRB-approved pre-screen instrument, the active trial's per-criterion conversational language, the active candidate's authenticated context (where the candidate has authenticated through the institution's portal; for non-authenticated outreach, only the candidate-provided study-interest data), access to a structured library of IRB-approved per-trial recruitment-content (trial-overview language, trial-specific FAQs, regulatory-disclaimer language at multiple reading levels and in multiple languages, visit-schedule descriptions, compensation descriptions, risk-summary language at the appropriate disclosure depth for the trial), and a careful set of tools for retrieving trial-specific content, scoring pre-screen responses against the trial's criteria, scheduling screening visits, escalating to the research coordinator, and emitting structured pre-screen results to the institution's clinical trial management system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one-trial. It is multi-trial: at any time, the institution may have dozens to hundreds of actively-recruiting trials, each with its own IRB-approved recruitment plan, scripts, pre-screen instrument, coordinator routing, and timeline. The bot is multi-tenant across trials, with per-trial governance enforced at every step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial-specific recruitment-context establishment.** The candidate enters the conversation in the context of a specific trial: through a recruitment-letter QR code, an SMS link, an EHR-portal recruitment notification, an institutional study-finder website, a partner physician referral, a recruitment-vendor channel, or a directly-typed-in trial identifier. The bot establishes which trial is in play and loads the trial's IRB-approved recruitment-content package, pre-screen instrument, and coordinator-routing configuration. The bot does not engage on a trial it does not have configuration for.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disclosure of nature and consent for engagement.** The bot identifies itself as a chat tool and not a person, identifies the institution and the trial, names the regulatory framing (the trial is research, not clinical care; the candidate's participation is voluntary; declining to engage will not affect the candidate's ongoing clinical care), names the privacy framing (information shared in the conversation will be used for pre-screening and may be shared with the research team; PHI handling follows the IRB-approved data plan), names the coordinator-handoff path (a research coordinator will be in touch if the candidate is interested and pre-screens positive), and asks the candidate's consent to engage. The candidate can decline at any time without consequence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved trial description delivery.** The bot delivers the IRB-approved study description, adapted to the candidate's preferred language and reading level. The description covers the research question (in plain language), the experimental treatment, the comparison arm (placebo or active comparator), randomization (in plain language with a clear "the experimental treatment is not guaranteed; you might receive placebo" disclosure where the design includes placebo), the visit schedule and time commitment, the compensation, the risks at the IRB-approved depth and level, the right to leave the study at any time, and the institution and study-team contact information. The description is delivered conversationally, with the candidate able to ask clarifying questions at any point. The clarifying answers are grounded in the IRB-approved per-trial recruitment-content corpus; off-script answers are not permitted.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Candidate-question handling within scope.** The candidate can ask questions about the trial. In-scope questions: questions about the visit schedule, the compensation, the experimental treatment at the IRB-approved disclosure depth, the comparison arm, the time commitment, the data-collection schedule, the trial team, the institution. Out-of-scope questions: questions that require clinical judgment about the candidate's specific medical condition, questions about whether they should join the trial (the bot describes the trial; the candidate decides), questions that require informed-consent-level depth (those happen with the consent-conversation clinician, not the bot), questions about other trials (handled separately in a multi-trial finder or routed to the coordinator).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured pre-screen against IRB-approved criteria.** When the candidate is interested, the bot conducts the trial's pre-screen instrument. The instrument is IRB-approved, deterministic in scoring, structured in output, and per-trial-specific. The bot asks each pre-screen question in IRB-approved language at the candidate's reading level and language preference, captures the response, and scores deterministically against the criterion. The bot does not freestyle pre-screen questions; the bot does not infer eligibility from off-instrument disclosures; the bot does not modify the instrument.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pre-screen disposition and warm handoff.** Based on the structured pre-screen result, the bot dispositions the candidate. Pass-and-interested: warm handoff to the research coordinator for screening-visit scheduling, with the structured pre-screen output, the conversation transcript, and the candidate's contact preferences attached. Fail-on-criterion: the bot delivers the IRB-approved fail-explanation language ("based on what you've shared, this particular study isn't a match, but thank you for your interest") with appropriate care to avoid disclosure of the specific failed criterion where IRB has scoped the disclosure (some criteria are sensitive). Pass-but-uncertain: warm handoff to the coordinator for clarifying conversation. Decline-to-engage: respectful exit, no further contact unless the candidate re-initiates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-trial finder where applicable.** When the candidate is engaging through a multi-trial entry point (study-finder website, EHR portal patient-research surface), the bot can conduct broader-interest discovery, surface multiple matching trials, and route to per-trial pre-screen. The multi-trial-finder is a different deployment shape from per-trial-link entry; some institutions deploy both.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator-side handoff with full context.** The research coordinator picks up the warm handoff with the candidate's structured pre-screen output, the conversation transcript, the IRB-approved-content version stamps, the candidate's stated preferences (preferred language, reading level, contact channel, time-of-day windows), and the candidate's contact information. The coordinator does not start over; the coordinator picks up where the bot left off.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Audit and CTMS integration.** Every conversation generates an audit record. Every pre-screen disposition generates a CTMS entry. Every handoff generates a coordinator-side queue entry. The audit, CTMS-integration, and coordinator-queue records are durable, version-stamped, and preserved per FDA SaMD post-market obligations and Common Rule recordkeeping requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No-further-contact discipline.** Candidates who decline to engage, or who fail pre-screen and are not eligible, are not pursued through other channels for the same trial unless the IRB-approved recruitment plan specifies otherwise. The do-not-contact discipline is operationalized.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Clinical-Trial Recruitment Conversation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it the trial's protocol document, prompt it with "you are a friendly recruiter for this study," and let it engage with candidates about whatever they bring. This breaks in several specific ways, each with regulatory, clinical, or ethical consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no IRB-approval discipline.** A generalist LLM, given a protocol, will paraphrase the study description in language that is plausible-sounding, reading-level-appropriate, and entirely outside what IRB has approved. The IRB-approved language is the architectural floor; the bot delivers from the IRB-approved per-trial recruitment-content corpus, not from its parametric memory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents content when grounding is weak.** A bot freestyling about visit schedules, compensation amounts, risks of the experimental treatment, or eligibility criteria is delivering content the IRB has not reviewed. The retrieval-grounded delivery with strict citation discipline is non-negotiable. Every assertion the bot makes is grounded in a cited IRB-approved per-trial content item with its IRB-approval date and version preserved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no structured pre-screen instrument.** Pre-screening is a structured assessment against IRB-approved criteria with deterministic scoring. The LLM, asked to "screen" a candidate, will conduct an unstructured conversation and infer eligibility, which is not what pre-screen is. The structured pre-screen tool encapsulates the instrument; the LLM gathers the inputs and the scoring is deterministic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no coercion-or-pressure detection.** A bot that says "this is a really great opportunity, you should definitely consider it" is being coercive in a way IRB explicitly prohibits. The system prompt, the output safety, and the IRB-reviewed content library together constrain the bot to non-coercive language; the generalist LLM, trying to be helpful, drifts coercive regularly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no benefit-promise discipline.** A bot that says "this treatment may help you with your diabetes" is making a benefit promise that IRB does not permit. The bot describes the trial; the bot does not predict the candidate's outcome. The output safety detects benefit-promise language; the system prompt explicitly forbids it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when not to engage.** Some questions are out of scope. A request for clinical judgment ("based on my health situation, do you think I'd benefit?"), a request to compare trials ("is this trial better than that other trial?"), a request for medication advice ("should I stop my metformin to enroll?"), a request for prognosis ("how bad will my diabetes get if I don't enroll?"). Each is outside scope. The bot recognizes the boundary and routes to the coordinator; the generalist LLM tries to be helpful and crosses the boundary regularly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of vulnerable-population protections.** Recruitment of pregnant patients, prisoners, children, cognitively-impaired adults, and other populations with vulnerability protections under the Common Rule has additional requirements. The bot, asked to recruit such populations, must follow the trial-specific IRB-approved special-population protocols. The generalist LLM has no awareness of these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of mandatory-reporting adjacency.** Some pre-screen conversations surface information that has mandatory-reporting implications (active suicidal ideation surfaced in the context of a depression trial; child-abuse disclosure in the context of a parenting trial). The bot must route to a licensed clinician with mandatory-reporting authority, not handle the disclosure as a recruitment-context event.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to research data.** The conversation contains research-context PHI: the fact that the candidate is being screened for a specific trial, the candidate's responses to pre-screen questions, the candidate's stated reasons for interest or decline. Research-context PHI is governed by HIPAA's preparatory-research provisions, the trial's IRB-approved data plan, and (where the trial is FDA-regulated) FDA's recordkeeping requirements. Some institutions classify research-context PHI in a separately-keyed, separately-governed enclave.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the do-not-contact discipline.** A candidate who has declined a specific trial does not get re-contacted for the same trial unless the IRB-approved recruitment plan specifies a re-contact protocol (some plans do, with a defined waiting interval; most do not). The generalist LLM has no awareness of this; the bot's data-handling pipeline operationalizes it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of trial-specific completeness.** Some trials require specific pre-screen depth (genetic testing pre-screen for some oncology trials, specific imaging history for some cardiology trials, specific lifestyle pre-screen for some metabolic trials). The trial-specific instrument captures this. The generalist LLM, trying to be conversational, may skip completeness and produce an unreliable pre-screen output.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the consent-conversation handoff.** The bot's role ends before the informed-consent process. The bot prepares the candidate to engage productively with consent; the consent process itself is human-led. A generalist LLM, asked an in-depth consent question, will try to answer it, which is not the bot's job.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the recruitment-vendor or partner-channel boundary.** Some trials use external recruitment vendors or partner-physician channels with specific data-flow and contracting agreements. The bot's interactions through those channels have specific governance constraints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the multi-site or multi-country variation.** Trials at multiple sites or in multiple countries have site-specific or country-specific IRB approvals, language requirements, and regulatory frameworks. The bot's per-site and per-country configuration captures this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the candidate's relationship to the institution.** The candidate may be an existing patient of the institution, a candidate referred from a partner provider, a self-identified candidate from a recruitment-website channel, or a candidate identified through a recruitment-vendor channel. Each relationship has different starting context, different consent posture, and different identity-assurance requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Recruitment Bot Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.9 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, identity verification (where applicable), tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, citation grounding, conversational identity-and-disclosure framing, warm handoff to humans for outside-scope topics. The recruitment bot adds nine structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved per-trial recruitment-content corpus as architectural primitive.** Each trial has its own IRB-approved content corpus with its own IRB approval date, version stamp, language-and-reading-level variants, and validity-window. The bot delivers from the corpus; the bot does not freestyle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved per-trial pre-screen instrument with deterministic scoring.** Each trial has its own IRB-approved pre-screen instrument with its own scoring rules. The bot administers the instrument; the bot does not modify it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-trial coordinator-routing configuration.** Each trial has its own research-coordinator team, its own coordinator-queue, its own escalation pathway, and its own scheduling-system integration. The bot routes per-trial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coercion, pressure, and benefit-promise detection and avoidance.** The bot's output safety includes detection of coercive language, pressure language, benefit-promise language, and standard-of-care-disparagement language. The IRB-approved content corpus does not contain such language; the bot does not generate it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Vulnerable-population protocols where applicable.** Trials enrolling vulnerable populations (children, pregnant patients, prisoners, cognitively-impaired adults) have special-population protocols. The bot enforces them per-trial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Do-not-contact discipline with operational enforcement.** Candidates who decline are not re-contacted for the same trial unless the IRB-approved plan specifies otherwise. The data-handling pipeline operationalizes this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Research-context PHI handling with separately-governed storage where required.** Research-context PHI is governed by HIPAA preparatory-research provisions, the trial's IRB-approved data plan, and FDA recordkeeping requirements. Storage is in separately-keyed, separately-access-controlled enclaves where the institution's policy requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **CTMS integration with structured pre-screen output.** The pre-screen disposition emits a structured record into the institution's clinical-trial management system, populating the candidate's pre-screen worksheet so the coordinator does not re-collect.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial-specific FDA and Common Rule alignment.** Trials regulated by FDA have FDA-specific recordkeeping. Trials with VA, DOD, NIH, or other federal-agency involvement have agency-specific provisions. International trials have country-specific provisions. The bot's per-trial configuration captures this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle (where applicable), conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Clinical-Trial Recruitment Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes recruitment specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The IRB-content-governance lifecycle is the critical path.** Before any conversation is possible, the trial's recruitment-script and pre-screen-instrument language has to be IRB-approved, in all supported languages and reading levels. IRB approval cycles typically run weeks to months. <!-- TODO: verify; IRB approval cycles for recruitment-material amendments vary substantially by institution and IRB; specific timelines vary --> Engineering work that pushes ahead of the IRB-content-governance lifecycle deploys against drafts that may change before launch. The architectural pattern is to treat the IRB-approved content corpus as a versioned external dependency that the bot consumes; engineering does not write the content, IRB does.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The pre-screen-instrument formalization is non-trivial clinical work.** A pre-screen instrument that scores deterministically against the trial's inclusion and exclusion criteria, in conversational form, is not a paraphrase of the protocol. It is a structured assessment with explicit branching logic, criterion-by-criterion deterministic scoring, and IRB-approved per-question language. Each criterion needs a question (or set of questions), a scoring rule, an unambiguous-fail disposition, an unambiguous-pass disposition, and an uncertain disposition that routes to coordinator-side clarification. Building this for a trial typically takes several weeks of clinical, regulatory, and design work, with IRB approval at the end.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The coordinator-handoff workforce is the architecture.** A bot deployed without coordinator capacity to convert the queue into screening visits is a bot that generates leads with no one to convert them. Coordinator-side capacity is sized to the bot's expected output, with appropriate buffer for the candidates who require above-baseline coordinator time. Under-sizing the coordinator workforce produces a deployment that has to throttle the bot, which defeats the throughput-improvement value proposition.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Demographic and equity considerations are not optional.** Clinical-trial demographics have been historically skewed in ways that affect the validity and generalizability of trial results. A recruitment bot can reach populations that traditional outreach has missed (non-English-preferred candidates, candidates with limited phone availability, candidates in geographic areas the institution has historically under-recruited from), or it can amplify existing disparities (candidates without smartphones, candidates with low digital-literacy comfort, candidates in populations with historically-justified mistrust of research institutions). <!-- TODO: verify; clinical-trial demographics including race, ethnicity, sex, and geographic representation have been the subject of FDA, NIH, and academic attention for decades, with ongoing initiatives to improve representation; specific findings vary --> Per-cohort monitoring with explicit equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trust in the research enterprise is variable, with deep historical reasons.** Some communities have historically-justified mistrust of research institutions, with U.S. research history including specific incidents that have permanently affected how communities engage with research recruitment. <!-- TODO: verify; the Tuskegee Syphilis Study and the Henrietta Lacks case are among many historical incidents that continue to affect community trust in research institutions, particularly among Black and other historically-underserved populations --> A recruitment bot deployed in communities with low baseline trust must engage with a different starting point than a recruitment bot deployed in communities with higher baseline trust. The institutional approach to building trust (community advisory boards, transparent engagement with concerns, trial designs that center community priorities) is part of the deployment, not adjacent to it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language and multi-reading-level deployment is non-optional for many trials.** Trials enrolling diverse populations require IRB-approved content in the trial's supported languages. Translation is not just translation; it is IRB-approved translation reviewed by the IRB and validated for cultural and clinical accuracy. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA and IRB requirements for translated recruitment materials include certified translation and back-translation review; specific requirements vary by IRB --> Multi-reading-level adaptation is similarly IRB-reviewed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Financial-incentive and compensation framing has specific regulatory considerations.** Compensation for trial participation is permitted but is regulated. The IRB-approved compensation language frames compensation as recognition of time and inconvenience, not as inducement. Bot language that frames compensation as a primary reason to participate crosses into coercion. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance on compensation for trial participation and IRB review of compensation language frame compensation as not constituting undue inducement; specific guidance varies -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Decentralized and hybrid trial designs add complexity.** Decentralized clinical trials (DCTs) and hybrid trials with home-based visits, remote-monitoring components, and remote-consent processes are increasing in prevalence. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance on decentralized clinical trials has been issued and continues to evolve; specific provisions vary by trial design --> The bot's interaction with DCT designs may include scheduling at-home visits, coordinating with remote-monitoring vendors, and routing to remote-consent processes. The DCT-specific configuration is per-trial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Industry-sponsored versus investigator-initiated versus federally-funded trials have different recruitment frameworks.** Industry-sponsored trials typically have sponsor-defined recruitment plans subject to site-IRB review; investigator-initiated trials have institution-specific recruitment plans; federally-funded trials may have agency-specific frameworks. The bot's per-trial configuration captures the trial's funding-source-specific constraints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Re-consent and protocol-amendment communication have specific recruitment-bot considerations.** When a trial protocol is amended, currently-enrolled participants may need re-consent, and recruitment messaging may need updating. The bot's content corpus per trial is updated upon protocol amendment and IRB re-approval; mid-flight conversations may need to pause and route to coordinator-side handling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Site-readiness and recruitment-bot-readiness are not the same.** Sites that are protocol-active are ready to enroll; sites that are recruitment-bot-active have additional configuration including coordinator-queue setup, IRB-approved-content uploaded, CTMS integration tested, and per-site routing configured. Bot deployment lags trial activation by site.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution to bot deployment is often weak.** Recruitment is multi-channel by design; the bot is one of several channels. Attributing enrollment improvements specifically to the bot requires careful design: matched-cohort comparisons (with bot exposure as the matched variable), staggered rollout (sites enabled at different times), or randomized comparison (some candidates randomized to bot-channel and some to traditional channel). Most institutions deploy with the recognition that observational improvements are suggestive rather than causal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ClinicalTrials.gov is the U.S. trial registry and a primary source of structured trial data.** The U.S. registry of federally and privately funded clinical trials provides structured data on trial design, eligibility criteria, locations, status, and contact information. <!-- TODO: verify; ClinicalTrials.gov is operated by the U.S. National Library of Medicine and is the U.S. trial registry under FDAAA and other statutes --> Bot-side integration with ClinicalTrials.gov is common for multi-trial finders and for verifying trial-status information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Common Rule (45 CFR 46) and FDA regulations (21 CFR Part 50, Part 56) govern human-subjects research in the U.S.** These frameworks include the IRB-review requirement, the informed-consent requirement, the special-population protections, and the recordkeeping requirements that frame the bot's regulatory posture. <!-- TODO: verify; the Common Rule and FDA regulations have specific provisions that vary by funding source, study type, and population; specific requirements vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **HIPAA's preparatory-research provisions permit limited use of PHI for recruitment with specific safeguards.** HIPAA's Privacy Rule includes provisions allowing covered entities to use PHI for activities preparatory to research, including identification of potential candidates, with specific procedural requirements. <!-- TODO: verify; HIPAA Privacy Rule preparatory-research provisions are in 45 CFR 164.512(i); specific procedural requirements vary --> The bot's PHI handling for cohort-identification and pre-outreach is governed by these provisions where applicable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial-management platforms have increasingly mature recruitment integration.** Vendors providing CTMS, eClinical, eConsent, ePRO, and EDC platforms have built recruitment-channel integration that bot deployments interoperate with. The institutional CTMS is the system of record for the candidate-and-enrollment lifecycle; the bot's structured pre-screen output emits to the CTMS.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle structured pre-screen and content delivery well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to recruitment. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve trial-specific content, retrieve the trial's pre-screen instrument, score pre-screen responses, schedule screening visits, propose coordinator handoff, emit pre-screen output to the CTMS, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA has issued recent guidance on patient-engagement and digital-recruitment tools.** FDA and other regulators have issued guidance and continue to refine expectations for digital recruitment tools, decentralized trial designs, and AI-mediated recruitment communication. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance on patient-engagement and decentralized trials has been issued and continues to evolve; specific provisions vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-focused recruitment initiatives have gained policy attention.** FDA, NIH, and other agencies have emphasized improving demographic representation in trials, with specific guidance, funding mechanisms, and reporting requirements. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA's Diversity Action Plan provisions, NIH's inclusion policies, and related initiatives have specific reporting and design requirements; specific provisions vary --> Bot deployments are well-positioned to support these initiatives or to undermine them depending on architectural choices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature in the recruitment-vendor space.** Recruitment-as-a-service vendors offer trial-specific recruitment campaigns, multi-channel outreach, and (increasingly) conversational recruitment surfaces. Most major institutions running their own recruitment-bot platform run a hybrid: build the trial-orchestration and IRB-content-governance layers in-house, partner with vendors for specific channel-execution, and integrate with the institution's CTMS, eConsent, and clinical-trial-financial-management infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
